<section class="card">
  <h2>About Tomatoes</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Warm-season crop—maturity depends on frost timing and accumulated heat.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Tomatoes are frost-tender and can be killed at 32°F (0°C).</strong>
    In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), tomato viability depends on transplanting after last frost, accumulating sufficient Growing Degree Days (GDD), and ripening fruit before first fall frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Tomatoes require a balance of time and heat. In short seasons, early indoor starts, disciplined transplant timing, and appropriate variety length determine whether fruit ripens with buffer before frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors:</strong> 6–8 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Transplant:</strong> 1–3 weeks after last frost (once nights are stable)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 55–100+ days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (killed at 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Cool nights and delayed transplanting shrink seasonal runway.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature & Growth Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~60°F (16°C) preferred</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–85°F (21–29°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~55°F (13°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Tomatoes stall in cool soil and cool nights. Early transplanting into marginal temperatures often delays flowering and fruit set,
    reducing risk margin before first frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost probability context, see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~1,200–1,800+ GDD (base 50), depending on variety and fruit size</p>

  <p>
    Tomatoes are moderately to strongly heat-dependent. Early varieties require fewer GDD, while large-fruited or long-season types require more.
    In cool summers, labeled “days to maturity” may extend significantly.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined frost + heat framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Tomato maturity ranges widely. Early varieties may ripen in <strong>55–70 frost-free days</strong>,
    while mid- to late-season types often require <strong>80–100+ days</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, choosing early or compact varieties is critical to preserving margin before first frost.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes, with early varieties</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless strong summer heat and early transplanting</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful (row cover early, warm microclimates)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Tomatoes have no frost tolerance buffer. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) can end production immediately and damage fruit.
    First frost is a hard seasonal boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Start indoors 6–8 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li>Transplant only after soil and nights have stabilized</li>
    <li>Select early or determinates in tight frost windows</li>
    <li>Use full sun and heat-retaining microclimates to increase effective GDD</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine">
    For transplant timing logic, see:
    <a href="/guides/when-to-transplant-seedlings-outdoors/">When to transplant seedlings outdoors</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, tomato viability depends on whether your frost-free window and seasonal heat budget exceed the crop’s maturity requirement.
    Early-season cold or late transplanting are common ways risk margin disappears.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can tomatoes survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Tomatoes are frost-sensitive and can be damaged or killed at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Why didn’t my tomatoes ripen before frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Most often, either the variety required more GDD than your climate provided, or transplant timing reduced seasonal runway.
  </p>

  <h3>Are early tomatoes more reliable in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Early varieties require fewer frost-free days and fewer accumulated GDD to reach maturity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Tomatoes are frost-sensitive and moderately heat-dependent.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 55–100+ days, ~1,200–1,800+ GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>